    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-06-26T15:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-06-26T15:30:00-05:00" n="906"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d906">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/6–2654: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Korea</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d906fn1">This telegram, which was drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_MRJG1">McClurkin</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName> and cleared by <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName>, was also sent to Tokyo as telegram 2876 with
                        instructions to pass to <gloss target="#t_CINCUNC1">CINCUNC</gloss>, to
                        Taipei as telegram 957, and to Saigon as telegram 2736.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-06-26T16:30:00-04:00"
                            >June 26, 1954—4:30 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1043. Secretary <persName corresp="#p_WCE1">Wilson</persName> has raised question
                    of what should now be done about plans for further redeployment US forces from
                    Korea which were suspended pending outcome Geneva Conference. Recent telegrams
                    from Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_HGJE1">General Hull</persName> have also suggested consideration
                    this subject.</p>
                <p>It is desired to continue deployment from Korea in accordance with the program
                    announced by the President on December 26<note n="2" xml:id="d906fn2">See
                        footnote 1 <ref target="#pg_1679">p. 1679</ref>.</note> under the safeguards
                    and reassurances which he then expressed. However, before making this decision
                    final in regard to a second state of deployment from Korea, I would like your
                    estimate as to whether it would be interpreted as a sign of weakness and if so,
                    whether any statements or explanations to be given at the time of announcements
                    would obviate this impression.</p>
                <p>President’s statement was transmitted by wireless bulletin FEF–2 Dec. 28,
                    1953.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
